organic_results.title: Sex and institutional differences in labor market effects on the expansion of higher education, 1952 to 1980
organic_results.snippet: This paper compares labor market effects on the expansion of higher education after World War II for men and women in two-and four-year institutions. The paper shows that across all groups, professional-technical employment had a positive effect on enrollment expansion. Contrary to the hypothesis that students in two-year schools provide a better surplus labor pool than students in four-year schools, I found few significant differences in the predictors of expansion in these two sectors.
